1215","1219":"1219","Abt 1239":"about 1239","Morton, Derby, England":"Morton, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thorpe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Yorkshire and Lancashire): from Middle English <i>thorp(e)</i> ‘village, hamlet, farmstead’ (Old Norse, Old English <i>thorp</i> ‘secondary settlement’). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in such a settlement, or habitational, for someone from any of several places called Thorp(e), which are most frequent in Yorkshire, the Midlands, and East Anglia. Compare   Throop  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Trupp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Hermann, Reinhold.","English (Herefordshire and Monmouthshire): variant of   Thorpe  , or from a place so named, such as Thrupp (Berkshire, Gloucestershire, Oxfordshire), Thrupe (Somerset), Throop (Dorset, Hampshire, Somerset), and Throope (Wiltshire).","Altered form of German   Trapp  ."]},{"name":"Throop","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>throp</i> ‘village, hamlet, farmstead’ (Old Norse, Old English <i>throp</i> ‘secondary settlement’). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in such a settlement, or habitational, for someone from Throop in Hampshire, Throope in Wiltshire, Thrup in Oxfordshire, or any of the places called Thrupp in Berkshire, Gloucestershire, and Northamptonshire. Compare   Thorpe  ."]},{"name":"Tharpe","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Thorpe  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Thorp","meanings":["English (mainly Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Thorpe  .","Scandinavian: variant of   Torp  ."]},{"name":"Troup","meanings":["Scottish (eastern): habitational name from a place in the parish of Gamrie, near Banff. The placename is unexplained, perhaps a Pictish cognate of Welsh <i>trwp</i> ‘vessel, dish, basin’.","Possibly also English, a metathesized form of   Thorpe  ."]},{"name":"Tharp","meanings":["English: variant of   Thorpe  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Thorpe was born about 1215, in Morton, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Mrs William Thorpe about 1239, in Morton, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"Abt 1215–":"umbes 1215–Surnud","1219–Female":"1219–Surnud","1242–Female":"1242–Surnud","1215–Male":"1215–Surnud","1215":"1215","Abt 1242":"umbes 1242","1242":"1242","Abt 1215":"umbes 1215","1219":"1219","Abt 1239":"umbes 1239","Morton, Derby, England":"Morton, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1215–":"noin 1215–Kuollut","1219–Female":"1219–Kuollut","1242–Female":"1242–Kuollut","1215–Male":"1215–Kuollut","1215":"1215","Abt 1242":"noin 1242","1242":"1242","Abt 1215":"noin 1215","1219":"1219","Abt 1239":"noin 1239","Morton, Derby, England":"Morton, Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1215–":"environ 1215–Décédé","1219–Female":"1219–Décédée","1242–Female":"1242–Décédée","1215–Male":"1215–Décédé","1215":"1215","Abt 1242":"environ 1242","1242":"1242","Abt 1215":"environ 1215","1219":"1219","Abt 1239":"environ 1239","Morton, Derby, Engl